Comment¶

Price vs. logPrice

  • Through the histogram and the boxplot, we can see that the price variable is right skewed with relatively high kurtosis. The distribution of price point out that there are many outliers. This could be observed through the maximum values of this column is more than ten times compared to the mean and nine times above the third outliers.
  • After plotting the distributions and looking at the summary statistics of price and logPrice for comparison, we find out that the log transformation has a significant effect on the price. By doing this way, the distribution of price becomes approximately symmetric with moderate tails. Thus, these results suggest that choosing log transformation over the original price will result in more reliable and efficient outcome when doing statistical inference including OLS method and other large sample approximations, because there is no asymmetry and the absence of outliers.
  • In addition, the skewness of our dependent variable might link with non-constant error variance and nonlinearity when we model its relationship with potential predictor variables.

Most and Least predictors

  • The most influential predictors for explaining house price is sqft - house living area in square meters. The larger the house, the more expensive. The Pearson correlation of 0.79 indicates strong linear relationship between these two variables. Analysis between price and logPrice versus sqft conducted through the scatter plot shows the benefit of log transformation where linear relationship is strengthened.

  • The least influential predictors could be dom - days on the market. Based on the correlation matrix, the Pearson correlation between logPrice and dom is 0.11. This predictors does not seem to affect house price since longer or shorter days on the market does not point out anything. And customers tends to focus the functionalities rather than how long it is there.

  • The scatter plots and correlation matrix from EDA points out strong relationship between logPrice and sqft, followed by baths and bedrooms.

  • For categorical variables, the boxplot between logPrice and other variables does not seem to point out significant relationship since these variables just make the price cluster around the mean of logPrice.

    • Occupancy: Price is higher for houses with owner, followed by vacant and tenant. This could be due to the fact that owner-occupied house are often in good conditions. Owner might have invested in the maintenance the house, which can attract more customers.
    • Waterfront: Price is higher for houses with waterfront. This is due to the location of these houses, which are usually on market with higher price. Waterfront house offers buyers with scenic view and easy access to water activity or beach life.
    • Fireplace and Pool: Same observation as above, price is higher for houses with fireplace and pool. These two features are supposed to gurantee the comfort of the house. Buyers who are looking for a high quality life tend to put these criterias on the check list.

Two sample t-test¶

In [32]:
ttest_ind(P0.price, P1.price, equal_var = False)
Out[32]:
Ttest_indResult(statistic=-3.905297448886061, pvalue=0.00021338179372696258)

Since the question asked for the comparison between price of house with/without waterfront, instead of using logPrice, I use the original price to point out the difference between two groups.

The hypotheses are:

$H_0:$ the two group means are equal: $\mu_{\text{no waterfront}} = \mu_{\text{waterfront}}$. $H_1:$ the two group means are not equal: $\mu_{\text{no waterfront}} < \mu_{\text{waterfront}}$.

We choose $\alpha=0.05$ as standard.

The test statistic is $t = 3.905$. The p-val is $< 0.05$, so we reject the null hypothesis and come to a conclusion that the mean of two groups are significantly different from each other. In other words, there is a significant relationship between house with waterfront and price.

Assumptions:

  • Data are i.i.d for each group: We assume this is true. Houses within with and without waterfront group are independent from each other, that is, house does not influence each other's price.
  • Two groups are independent of each other: We assume that houses with waterfont do not affect the price of house without waterfront and vice versa.
  • The 4th moment of price is finite: The boxplot of price and waterfront shows that there are quite a few outliers at the right tail. Hence, this assumption does not satisfy.

Thus, as long as the last assumption does not satisfy, the t-test for difference in means is not valid. Since the 4th moment assumption does not satisfy, we might find the usefulness of log transformation of price, which can be used for model in below tasks.

Median test¶

In [33]:
median_test(P0.price, P1.price, ties = "ignore")
Out[33]:
(39.68854775470324,
 2.978670543157528e-10,
 130000.0,
 array([[429,  61],
        [478,   9]]))

The hypotheses are:

$H_0: \text{median}_\text{no waterfront} = \text{median}_\text{waterfront}$ vs $H_1: \text{median}_\text{no waterfront} \neq \text{median}_\text{waterfront}$.

We choose $\alpha = 0.05$ as standard and consistency across different tests.

The test statistic is $39.689$, which under the null follows a $\chi^2_1$ distribution. In this case, the p-value is is $P(\chi^2_1 > 39.689) = 2.979 \times 10^{-10}$. Since, the p-value is much less than $< 0.05$, we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that there is a significant difference in median between $price$ for houses without waterfront and with waterfront.

Assumptions made include:

  1. Independence of the two groups: We assume this is true. Houses with waterfront do not affect the price of houses without waterfront.

  2. Data are i.i.d. in each group: We assume this is true. A house in whichever group does not affect each other's price.

  3. Each cell in the contingency table has expected value at least 5. The test output gives the observed count for each cell, [429, 61] and [478, 9]. The result means that in group without waterfront, there are 429 observations are below the overall median (given as 130000 in the test result) and 61 are above the overall median. Same for the other group. The expected count for each cell will be calculated as (row total $\times$ column total)/total. Follow the formula, we know that for all cells, the expected count is greater than 5. One thing to notice, $N$ = 986, however, in this result, the total is just 977, this may be due to some value that are not greater or less than median, but is exactly equal to the median.

  4. Data are at least on the ordinal scale: price is a numerical variable, so this is satisfied.

Thus, since all assumptions are satisfied, the median test is valid.

Mann-Whitney U test¶

In [34]:
mannwhitneyu(P0.price, P1.price, alternative='less')
Out[34]:
MannwhitneyuResult(statistic=14843.5, pvalue=3.2709598038888467e-14)

The hypotheses are:

$H_0:$ $price$ in group without waterfront has the same distribution as $price$ in group with waterfront: $P(P_0 > P_1) = 0.5$; vs

$H_1:$ $price$ in group without waterfront does not have the same distribution as $price$ in group with waterfront: $P(P_0 > P_1) < 0.5$.

We choose $\alpha = 0.05$ as standard and consistency across different tests.

The test statistic assesses whether there is a difference in the sum of the ranks in each group. We can see that $U = 14843.5$. In this case, the p-value is roughly $1$, which is the one-sided p-value from a standard normal distribution. This p-value is very small, p-value < 0.05, and thus, we reject the null hypothesis that the two groups have the same distribution. We conclude that there is significant difference in distribution of price between houses with waterfront and houses without.

The assumptions made are:

  1. Data are i.i.d. in each group: We assume this is true. Houses within with and without waterfront group are independent from each other, that is, house does not influence each other's price.
  2. Independence of the two groups: We assume that houses with waterfont do not affect the price of house without waterfront and vice versa.
  3. Each group's sample size is large enough for the CLT to work: Our dataset is quite large with total observations is 986.
  4. Data are at least on the ordinal scale: price is a numerical variable, so this is satisfied.

Comment¶

Although the t-test is powerful, our data has quite a fews outliers which makes the assumptions for this test does not satisfy. It has a lower p-value than the MWU. We also know that the median test is the least powerful. MWU is not as powerful as the t-test, however, since all assumptions are satisfied, we come to a conclusion that the MWU test is the most reliable test among these three. We find out that price of houses without waterfront are significantly different from houses with waterfront.

Run the significant test for the slope separately by calling the t_test method of the model object reg1.

In [38]:
hypothesis = 'sqft = 0'
t_test = reg1.t_test(hypothesis)  # 2-sided t-test  H0: beta_1 = 0
print(t_test)

                             Test for Constraints                             
==============================================================================
                 coef    std err          t      P>|t|      [0.025      0.975]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
c0             0.0004   1.02e-05     40.462      0.000       0.000       0.000
==============================================================================

  • The null hypothesis is: $H_0: \beta_1 = 0$ vs $H_1: \beta_1 \neq 0$,

  • Since no direction is given in the question. $\alpha = 0.05$ as standard. The test statistics is $$t-stat = \frac{\hat{\beta_1}}{SE (\hat{\beta_1})} = \frac{0.0004}{1.02 \times 10^{-5}} = 40.462,$$ with 986 - 2 = 984 degrees of freedom.

  • The two-sided p-value is $2 \times P(t_{984} > 40.462) = 0.000$. Since $p-val < \alpha= 0.05$ we reject the null and conclude at $95\%$ confidence level that there is a significant effect from the house living area to the logPrice.

  • This test assumed all 5 LSA, including a constant error variance.

Comment¶

OLS assumption

  1. Linearity: Since the $R^2$ is 62.5%, it indicates that LSA 1 is satisfied and this is a strong fit.
  2. Exogeneity: The residual plot does not appear to display any clear patterns, nor does it display any clear changing variance (heteroskedasticity). A tendency of homoscedasticity is observed here. Hence, LSA 2 are pretty satisfied.
  3. Independence: This assumption makes sure that the data pair are i.i.d. The sqft does not display any clear trend, but they have a local mean close to 0 and rarely deviating from that point during the whole period.
  4. 4th moment exists: Outliers are controlled in this dataset by using the log transformation of price, which makes the dataset become normally distributed with rare outliers and avoid right-skewed as in normal price. Hence, LSA 4 is satisfied.
  5. Constant error variance: This assumption is about homoscedasticity. Since the points are randomly distributed and there is no clear trends, we can assume that LSA 5 is well satisfied.

LAD assumption

The LAD estimator assumes:

  1. Linearity: $Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X + \varepsilon$ is the true population linear model.
  2. The median of $\varepsilon | X$ $=0$
  3. Independence: The data pairs $Y_i, X_i$ are i.i.d.
  4. Continuity of density: $p(Y_i|X_i)$ is a continuous function.
  5. 1st absolute moment of Y exists: $E(|Y|)$ exists, i.e. is finite $< \infty$.
  6. 2nd moment of X exists: $E(X^2)$ exists, i.e. is finite $< \infty$.

  • The residual plot suggests that the typical residual is 0 for each value of $X = $ sqft, so assumptions 1 and 2 seem reasonable for this data. It makes sense when the living area has a great impact on the price of houses.

  • Assumption 3 is satisfied as the data pairs are independent from each other.

  • Assumption 4 requires a continuous density function. Since we do not know $p(Y|X)$, we will assume this to be true.

  • Assumptions 5 and 6 are weaker compared to the moment requirements for OLS estimation. According to the log transformation as seen in the histogram and the boxplot, we can observe that the level of outliers is slighly extreme. Therefore, assumption 5 or 6 are satisfied.

Slope test

  • The null hypothesis is $H_0: \beta_1 = 0$ vs $H_1: \beta_1 \neq 0$, since no direction is given in the question. $\alpha = 0.05$ (common choice).

  • The OLS-based test statistics is $$t-stat = \hat{\beta_1} / SE (\hat{\beta_1}) = 0.0004 / 1.02 \times 10^{-5} = 40.462$$

    with 986 - 2 = 984 degrees of freedom.

  • The p-value is $2P(t_{984} > 40.462) = 0.000$. Since $\text{p-val} < \alpha=0.05$, we reject the null (at $95\%$ confidence level) and conclude that there is a significant effect between the house living area and the price. This test assumed all 5 LSA, including a constant error variance.

  • The LAD-based test statistics is $$t-stat = \hat{\beta_1} / SE (\hat{\beta_1}) = 0.0004 / 9.6 \times 10^{-6} = 42.780$$

    with 986 - 2 = 984 degrees of freedom.

  • The p-value is $2P(t_{984} > 42.780) = 0.000$. Since $\text{p-val} < \alpha=0.05$ we reject the null (at $95\%$ confidence level) and conclude that there is a significant between the house living area and the price. This test assumed all 6 LAD assumptions above, but not a constant error variance.

Overall, we can conclude that there is hardly any difference between OLS and LAD. The scatter plot between OLS residuals vs logPrice and LAD residuals vs logPrice is identical. Clearly, the SE of $\hat{\beta}_1$ has changed at a small scale between the LAD and OLS estimation methods, neither has the estimate itself. The assumptions for both method are also satisied.

OLS method

Moreover, the adjusted R-squared of 0.676 suggests that the model is not overfitting after including another independent variables. The SER is 0.293 as above.

The effect of variable can be summarised as:

  1. Keeping all other variables constant, an increase of 1 meter of the house size is associated with an average increase in the price of 0.0003%.
  2. Keeping all other variables constant, an increase of 1 bathroom in the house is associated with an average increase in the price of 0.2774%.

Slope test $\beta_1$

  • The null hypothesis is $H_0: \beta_1 = 0$ vs $H_1: \beta_1 \neq 0$, since no direction is given in the question. $\alpha = 0.05$ (common choice).

  • The OLS-based test statistics for $\hat{\beta_1}$ is $$t-stat = \hat{\beta_1} / SE (\hat{\beta_1}) = 0.0003 / 1.34 \times 10^{-5} = 21.893$$

    with 986 - 2 = 984 degrees of freedom.

  • The p-value is $2P(t_{984} > 21.893) = 0.000$. Since $\text{p-val} < \alpha=0.05$, we reject the null (at $95\%$ confidence level) and conclude that there is a significant effect between the house living area and the price. This test assumed all 5 LSA, including a constant error variance.

Slope test $\beta_2$

  • The null hypothesis is $H_0: \beta_2 = 0$ vs $H_1: \beta_2 \neq 0$, since no direction is given in the question. $\alpha = 0.05$ (common choice).

  • The OLS-based test statistics for $\hat{\beta_2}$ is $$t-stat = \hat{\beta_1} / SE (\hat{\beta_1}) = 0.2774 / 0.02 = 12.633$$

    with 986 - 2 = 984 degrees of freedom.

  • The p-value is $2P(t_{984} > 12.633) = 0.000$. Since $\text{p-val} < \alpha=0.05$ we reject the null (at $95\%$ confidence level) and conclude that there is a significant between the number of baths in house and the price. This test assumed all 6 LAD assumptions above, but not a constant error variance.

Overall, this model is better than the SLR in predicting house price based on house living area and the number of baths in the house.

Comment¶

Another predictor that has a strong relationship with logPrice, along with sqft and baths is bedrooms.

MLR

The estimated multiple linear regression is:

\begin{align*} \widehat{\log(\text{Price})}&=\underset{(0.047)}{10.6261}+\,\underset{(1.52 \times 10^{-5})}{0.0003}\times\text{sqft} +\underset{(0.022)}{0.2837}\times\text{baths}+\underset{(0.018)}{-0.0321}\times\text{bedrooms} \end{align*}

The R-squared is 0.678, and the adjusted R-squared is 0.677.

  • The parameter for sqft is the same as previous model. The parameter for baths is slighly increased compared to the previous one. The slope for bedrooms is -0.0321.

  • The adjusted R-squared is 0.677, which has increased by 0.1% from the previous model. This suggests that adding $bedrooms$ to the model leads to this improvement.

The effect of variable can be summarised as:

  1. Keeping all other variables constant, an increase of 1 meter of the house size is associated with an average increase in the price of 0.0003%.
  2. Keeping all other variables constant, an increase of 1 bathroom in the house is associated with an average increase in the price of 0.2837%.
  3. Keeping all other variables constant, an increase of 1 bedroom in the house is associated with an average decrease in the price of 0.0321%.

Slope test

Significant test for $\beta_3$

  • The null hypothesis is: $H_0: \beta_3 = 0$ vs $H_1: \beta_3 \neq 0$,

  • Since no direction is given in the question. $\alpha = 0.05$ as standard. The test statistics is $$t-stat = \frac{\hat{\beta_1}}{SE (\hat{\beta_1})} = \frac{-0.0321}{0.018} = -1.769,$$ with 986 - 2 = 984 degrees of freedom.

  • The two-sided p-value is $2 \times P(t_{984} > -1.769) = 0.077$. Since $p-val > \alpha= 0.05$ we fail to reject the null and conclude that at $95\%$ confidence level that $\beta_3$ is not significantly different from 0.
  • The test assumed all 6 LSA.

Multicollinearity

  • Since P > |t| for bedrooms is higher than 0.05, we might have indentified the multicollinearity in the model. This is due to high correlation between predictors, which is highlighted in the correlation matrix in Task 1. OLS assumption includes each variables are independent of each other, however, the high correlation between predictors point out that this fact has violated the assumption.

  • Moreover, by using VIF, since p = 3 and VIFs of three features are 2.57, 2.05 and 1.87, which is in the middle of the scale 1-5, we can say that there are multicollinearity between these variables.

  • This can be explained by understanding that when living area is large, there will be more bedrooms and bathrooms. At the same time, as bathrooms usually go with bathrooms at ratio 1:1, we migh expect a relationship between bedrooms and bathrooms.

Overall, this is a strong fit since we have witnessed an increase in $R^2$ and $\text{adj.} R^2$. However, this model exists multicollinearity, which makes it performs not as good as model 2.

Answer:¶

From Task 1, we have found out that the most influential predictors in predicting house price is sqft - house living area, followed by number of bathrooms and bedrooms. Some other predictors such as waterfront, pool, fireplace or occupancy could also increase the house price a little bit. When we do MLR, adding predictors helps improving the $R^2$. All LSAs for three models are satisfied.

When we do an experiment on the test data, since the RMSE for model 1 is the lowest, we can conclude that model 1 is the best model in predicting house price. After fitting the SLR and MLR using OLS and LAD, we can find a relatively strong relationship between house price, and house living area.

If I were a property investor, these could be the strategies when buying house to maximise the capital gain:

  1. Potential house fits with characteristics: This could include looking for houses with the characteristics that we have outlined - large living areas. Since this features act as the main predictors of house price, investing in those houses will be benefit in long terms. Also, it is also beneficial to look at house with many features such as waterfront, pool or fireplace, which can increase the price.

  2. Location: As we have observed in the EDA in task 1, we could see that house in good locations, i.e waterfront, always have price that are fairly higher than others. Hence, it is necessary to check the potential growth of the suburbs.

  3. Renovation: It is also a good idea to invest in house with low price and start renovating later. This renovation could consists of increase the house living area, adding more bathrooms/bedrooms or making a pool. By doing this, we could increase the price of the house and thus, resulting in capital gain when they are on market.

  4. Buy at low price, sale at high price: Look for houses that have observed price that are below the predicted price from the model. These house could be underestimated in values, hence, a bargain for investors if we invest in something similar and sell at higher price as we have predicted.
